==English==

===Etymology 1===
Late 17th century, unknown origin, possibly {{Cy.}} {{term|moedrodd|lang=cy}} to worry or bother. Possible alternative from the {{Cy.}} {{term|meidda||to beg for whey|lang=cy}} or perhaps {{term|meiddio||to dare or venture|lang=cy}}. Bear in mind that the "dd" in Welsh corresponds in sound to the "th" in mither.

====Pronunciation====
*{{IPA|/ˈmaɪθər/}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|mithers|mithering|mithered|mithered}}

# {{context|intransitive|Northern England}} To make an [[unnecessary]] [[fuss]], [[moan]].
# {{transitive}} To [[pester]] or [[irritate]] someone. Usually directed at [[children]].
#: ''"Will you stop '''mithering''' me!"''

